<HEAD>PRESIDENT's ANSWER.</HEAD>
<OPENER><SALUTE>GENTLEMEN,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>I RECEIVE, with great &s;en&s;ibility, your addre&s;s on the &s;ub|ject of the treaty lately negociated between the United States and Great Britain, expre&s;&s;ing your confidence in the con|&s;tituted authorities, and the concurrence of your opinions with their determinations, on this highly important &s;ubject. Such &s;en|timents, deliberately formed, and proceeding from men who&s;e intere&s;ts are more immediately concerned than tho&s;e of any other cla&s;&s;es of my fellow citizens, cannot fail to &s;trengthen that ju&s;t confidence in the rectitude of public mea&s;ures, which is e&s;&s;ential to the general welfare.</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>Go. WASHINGTON.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
